forEach() Method in Java Stream API

forEach() is a terminal operation that performs an action on each element of a stream.

👉 It processes every element and returns nothing.

Method Signature
void forEach(Consumer<? super T> action)

Let's break it down:

void

forEach() returns nothing.

Consumer<? super T>

The method accepts a Consumer.

A Consumer:

@FunctionalInterface
public interface Consumer<T> {
    void accept(T t);
}

👉 Takes one value and performs an action.

Basic Example
List<String> fruits =
        List.of("Apple", "Banana", "Orange");

fruits.stream()
      .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

Apple
Banana
Orange
What Happens Internally

This:

fruits.stream()
      .forEach(System.out::println);

is similar to:

for (String fruit : fruits) {
    System.out.println(fruit);
}
Using Lambda
fruits.stream()
      .forEach(fruit -> System.out.println(fruit));
Using Method Reference

Instead of:

fruit -> System.out.println(fruit)

you can write:

System.out::println

Full example:

fruits.stream()
      .forEach(System.out::println);
forEach() Is a Terminal Operation

This is important.

fruits.stream()
      .filter(f -> f.startsWith("A"))
      .forEach(System.out::println);

👉 The stream starts executing only when forEach() is reached.

Without a terminal operation:

fruits.stream()
      .filter(f -> f.startsWith("A"));

Nothing happens.

forEach() with Objects
List<Person> people = List.of(
        new Person("John"),
        new Person("Alice")
);

people.stream()
      .forEach(person ->
              System.out.println(person.getName()));
Common Use Cases
Printing
list.forEach(System.out::println);
Logging
list.forEach(item ->
        logger.info(item));
Updating Objects
people.forEach(person ->
        person.setActive(true));
Difference Between map() and forEach()
map()

Transforms data.

list.stream()
    .map(String::toUpperCase);

Input:

apple

Output:

APPLE
forEach()

Performs an action.

list.stream()
    .forEach(System.out::println);

Input:

apple

Output:

apple

👉 No transformation.

Stream Example
List<String> result =
        fruits.stream()
              .filter(f -> f.startsWith("A"))
              .map(String::toUpperCase)
              .toList();

Here:

filter() selects data
map() transforms data

If we only want to print:

fruits.stream()
      .filter(f -> f.startsWith("A"))
      .forEach(System.out::println);
Common Interview Questions
Is forEach() terminal or intermediate?

✅ Terminal

What functional interface does forEach() use?

✅ Consumer

What does forEach() return?

✅ void

Can forEach() modify elements?

✅ Yes, if objects are mutable.

Summary
forEach() processes every element in a stream
accepts a Consumer
returns void
is a terminal operation
commonly used for:
printing
logging
executing actions
does not transform data
